    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Ellen Grove sits approximately 17 kilometres south-west of the Brisbane CBD, positioned in the outer western corridor alongside Forest Lake, Doolandella, Richlands, Inala and Durack. It is a suburb shaped almost entirely by residential estate development from the 1990s and 2000s: brick and tile homes on usable blocks, estate streetscapes, shared parks and the community infrastructure that planned development creates. The dominant buyer is a young family with a pre-approval, a clear view of what they need and a comparison set that spans the entire outer western corridor from Richlands south to Forest Lake.</p>

      <p>Sellers who understand that comparison set and position their campaign correctly within it consistently outperform those who run a generic listing and wait. This is a price-sensitive, internet-researched market. Buyers in Ellen Grove have typically watched comparable properties for several months before making an offer, and an overpriced listing does not attract patience. It attracts nothing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Ellen Grove</h2>
      <p>The primary Ellen Grove buyer in 2026 is a young family typically with primary-school-age children or younger. They are buying on a brief that includes a backyard of meaningful size, practical motorway access for commuting, and a price that is lower than the comparable results now being achieved in Forest Lake's newer estate pockets. They come with a pre-approval, have been watching the corridor for two to four months, and are ready to move when the right property appears at the right price.</p>

      <p>A second buyer profile is the first home buyer comparing Ellen Grove against Richlands and Doolandella at the same budget. They want a freestanding house on a proper block and Ellen Grove's modern estate stock delivers that. Investors are also present: the rental market in the outer western corridor is consistent, and yields here attract a buyer segment looking for positive cash-flow assets. The campaign positioning should lead with owner-occupier appeal, but investor logic should not be underestimated at the inspection stage.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Ellen Grove</h2>
      <p>Estate presentation is the first value driver. Ellen Grove's modern housing stock competes directly against comparable properties in Forest Lake and Richlands, and the buyer comparing three or four listings on the same weekend will notice immediately when a property has been maintained to a standard consistent with the estate versus one that has slipped. Deferred maintenance is a discount, not a private matter.</p>

      <p>Block size and usability are the second driver. Families buying here are doing so specifically because they want a meaningful backyard, room for a pool and space for children to play. Flat, usable blocks that can accommodate all of that without significant earthworks or landscaping investment attract a clear buyer premium over sloped or constrained sites at the same land area. The third driver is internal layout: open-plan living with a practical indoor-outdoor connection reads as move-in ready to the young family buyer, while segmented or dated layouts require more imagination and invite lower offers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Ellen Grove home for sale</h2>
      <p>Ellen Grove buyers are comparing your property directly against Forest Lake and Richlands at the same budget, and that comparison starts online before they ever attend an inspection. Properties that photograph well, with a clean exterior, tidy gardens, a clear sense of the indoor-outdoor connection and a presentation that signals estate maintenance rather than estate neglect, attract significantly more inspection attendance than those that present as tired or cluttered.</p>

      <p>For modern estate homes, the starting condition matters a great deal. The buyer who specifically chose Ellen Grove for its estate character wants to buy into a well-maintained example of it. Any visible deferred maintenance signals risk. Address the routine items before listing: repaint where necessary, fix what has been on the list, pressure-wash the driveways and outdoor areas, and clean the gutters. The pre-sale investment in a professional clean and basic staging of the main living areas and outdoor entertaining space consistently pays back in this market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Ellen Grove</h2>
      <p>Ellen Grove's family buyer market has clear peaks. Autumn from March through May is typically the strongest window: buyers who started searching after the Christmas break are ready to commit by March, competing stock across the outer western corridor is below the spring peak, and properties launched in this window face a prepared buyer pool without the distraction of multiple new listings appearing simultaneously. Spring from September through November brings the highest volume of buyer activity and the highest open home attendance, which is useful for generating competition on a well-prepared property. The weakest windows are the school holiday periods, particularly January and the mid-year break. Ellen Grove's school-age family buyer is genuinely school-calendar-driven. Launching a campaign in those windows means fewer of your best buyers are actively looking.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Ellen Grove</h2>
      <p>Well-presented, accurately priced Ellen Grove homes typically sell within 28 to 45 days. The suburb has a consistent buyer pool from the broader outer western corridor, and a property correctly positioned relative to recent comparable sales in Ellen Grove, Forest Lake and Richlands will attract inquiry within the first two weeks of a well-run campaign. Modern estate homes in clean condition sell at the faster end of that range: the buyer who wants that property type is well-defined and prepared to act. Properties with dated presentation or that require noticeable updating take longer, because the renovation-ready buyer pool in this corridor is more selective and needs the pricing to clearly account for the work ahead. This is a transparent, price-sensitive market. Buyers here have done their research and an overpriced listing will underperform even with good presentation. Accurate pricing is more important in Ellen Grove than in many comparable inner-city markets.</p>

